column1: How many worker protests will the China Labor Bulletin record from 1 May 2016 to 1 November 2016?
column5: ['Between 1,200 and 2,000, inclusive', 'Between 3,000 and 5,000, inclusive', ' More than 5,000', 'Fewer than 1,200', 'More than 2,000 but less than 3,000']
column6: ['Non-US Politics']

The CLB reports roughly 180-200 protests a month in 2016, since peaking at over 500 in January. The CLB would need to report 230 or so incidents in October to reach a number over 1200. This is possible but not in line with the recent trend.
To exceed 1200 there would have to be 237 protests in October. So far there's been only 65. It seems highly unlikely that there would be 172 protests in the last 7 days of the month.
By my count Total May - September = 963, so >236 necessary to reach 1,200. Incidents for Oct so far (10/26) is 65. Since May the highest monthly count was 209, therefor >236 v. unlikely.

There are 834 worker protests as of today, but the instructions in the More Info for finding the number are wrong. The CLB Strike Map filters by one month "to" another month, not "through" another month. If you filter 2016-5 to 2016-10, you only get 5 months. You want to filter 2016-5 to 2016-11. in 2015 and 2014, the number of strikes increased in the fall, but it doesn't seem to be this year. Only 51 strikes so far in September.

Wal-Mart workers back on the job (for now). http://www.reuters.com/article/us-walmart-china-idUSKCN0ZN26C May June total: 369 (so far).

July news: http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d1dd7376-4408-11e6-9b66-0712b3873ae1.html#axzz4DpqPRquP http://finance.yahoo.com/news/striking-wal-mart-workers-china-092227233.html Walmart staff across China start wild cat strikes over work hours (although the story only lists 3 incidents to date). Main issue is "flexible scheduling of an unlimited number of hours a day totaling up to 174 hours a month, with no overtime pay." Not sure how big an issue this will be since 174 / 8 indicates 22 eight hour work days a month, which, in the US is standard. So the issue is the distribution of the hours across the month. Slightly raising the forecast for the 1,200 - 2,000 bucket until the extent of future strikes can be better estimated. As of 7/8/16 the "Strike Map" lists the following 3 Wal-Mart incidents: 7/1- Store 5782, 7/2- Store 2039, 7/4-Store 0209.
Trend for last few weeks is to just undershoot. Obviously one to watch very carefully though.

If we take the average of two last year... 2015 & 2014 / 2 = 1039 the same number as last year 2015 for the period = 1209 2015 * the average of increase for each month since 2011= 1460 y = 4,4405 - 41,644 for each month of the period= 1503,57 the average of increase annually for each month since 2011 (122%) * month of 2015= 2447
Roughly 200 per month now, with previous years indicating stable number over the summer while having a slow continuous increase between years. Leads to an estimate of 1.2k or slightly above.

Observations from the 1990s: "... the most important mechanism of mobilization is the presence of coordinators or organizers ... Many of them do not have much experience in dealing with bureaucrats. Hence, [laid-off workers] need representatives who are able to negotiate with the government and ... initiators or organizers of .. collective action include current [small state-owned] entreprise leaders, previous entreprise cadres, retired workers, military veterans, non-cadre Party members and common workers. Most of them are ... more influential than the rank and file ... they are willing to become organizers [for] a combination of their personal stake in the action, community pressure, and some sense of justice. ... [and only after] if the whole [state-owned] entreprise goes bankrupt, closes production or ceases to pay its workers. Hence, many workers are affected simultaneously and consensus building among them is easier ... In contrast, workers who are laid off sequentially are often able to receive subsidies, because their entreprises are still in operation ... if the number of workers laid off each time is large, it is tantamount to simultaneous lay-offs ... "

Last year, based on the accepted source, there were 1207 such incidents in a similar period: 199 in May, 178 in June, 168 in July, 205 in August, 227 in September, and 230 in October. It's too early to say something about this year, but there was an increase in 2015, compared with 2014. More precisely, there were 704 incidents in the reference period in 2014. That is nearly a doubling. If the acceleration would hold, we should expect something like 2000+ incidents this year. I don't expect a similar swelling, since 2015 was rather flat, but still I guess that there is still an element of novelty, and uptake will go up. I am centering my expectation at an average of 1800, until I see the first few months of 2016 data.

initial forecast. I count 1208 over the same period last year, with the year-on-year trend increasing, and 1721 between 1st November 2015 and 20th April 2016. My rough guesstimate is that around the 2k mark is probably most likely, unlikely to be very substantially lower or higher.

This largely depends on CLB's capacity to find and record; not on how many incidents actually happen. In other words, we're predicting an organization's ability. This is akin to whether Apple would sell X amounts of iPhones by date Z. A 200-incidents-per-month average rate implies a capacity to find and identify six incidents a day. Today, it's the 117th day of the year and they have around 900 incidents, that is 900/117 = 8 incidents per day. In an NGO-like four hours workday, that's two incidents per hour.

The overall pattern of protests is a somewhat gradual increase until October of last year, followed by a sudden spike until January, followed by a decline to the present. Here are some estimates, depending on if the number of protests/month 1. ...continues to decline at the same rate: less than 500 protests expected 2. ... is the same as the last month around 500 protests 3. ... is the same as the same month last year: around 1200 protests 4. ... increases at the same rate over the same month last year that last year's did: around 1700 protests 5. ... increases at the historical average rate over the same month last year: 3000 protests 6. ... is the same as the maximum month ever recorded, every month: 3000 protests

initial thoughts. CLB article indicates large run-up in protests leading up to Chinese New Year, frequency reported has fallen off since then. Only half of April in the map yet though - so looks like good chance of >200/month average, but also possible to fall below. Over 3000 would represent more than double same time period in 2015, which had just over 1200 on the map. CLB map is based on social media and is believed to capture 10-15% of protests.
